<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="222" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1686,2037]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="221" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1686,1712]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[352,456,1687,1713]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete with 8 thoracic and 22 abdominal chaetigers. Total body length 
<quantity box="[1288,1355,1687,1713]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, crown 
<quantity box="[151,240,1722,1749]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
; maximum body width 
<quantity box="[506,592,1723,1749]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[607,712,1723,1749]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1585,1609]" captionTargetBox="[165,1419,281,1556]" captionTargetId="figure-61@19.[157,1430,273,1562]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 14. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636172" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636172/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Fig. 14A</figureCitation>
). Crown holding five pairs of radioles with 11 pairs of short pinnules arranged in two alternating rows of similar length (between 1/5 and 1/4 of the total radiolar length. The gap between pairs remains quite constant along the radiole. First basal pair and last distal pair with pinnules shorter than that in the medial radioles. Elongated radiolar tip, reaching more than 1/3 of the total radiolar length and of uniform width, and with a blunt tip (
<figureCitation box="[465,569,1867,1893]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1585,1609]" captionTargetBox="[165,1419,281,1556]" captionTargetId="figure-61@19.[157,1430,273,1562]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 14. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636172" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636172/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Fig. 14C</figureCitation>
). Radiolar skeleton with two rows of cells. Dorsal lips with long and pointed dorsal radiolar appendages (1/3 of crown length). Anterior peristomial ring with similar height all around, visible also on ventral side. Posterior peristomial ring elongate and connected to high ventral basal flanges, which extends as prominent ridge from base of ventralmost radioles (
<figureCitation box="[754,888,1974,2001]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Fig. 15D, E</figureCitation>
). Peristomial eyes not visible, pygidial eyes present, as very small spots on lateral margins of pygidium. Thorax longer than wide. The first thoracic chaetiger bearing only 3 chaetae similar in shape to the thoracic superior chaetae. From the second to the eighth thoracic chaetiger, 6 uncini on each torus with well-developed breast, and approximately four rows of similar teeth above main fang, large space to main fang, handle elongated, substantially longer than 1/3 of the total uncinus length and considered long handles (0.52) (
<figureCitation box="[384,488,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
). Companion chaetae present, with straight shaft and long mucro (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1334,258,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15B</figureCitation>
). Second to eighth thoracic chaetigers with 4 chaetae, one superior broadly hooded chaeta (
<figureCitation box="[1072,1176,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15D</figureCitation>
), and three inferior paleate chaetae with a short mucro, long slightly less than the hood (
<figureCitation box="[899,1001,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15E</figureCitation>
). Four abdominal uncini on each torus with similar-sized small teeth above the main fang and medium handle (
<figureCitation box="[955,1057,366,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15C</figureCitation>
). Four abdominal broadly hooded neurochaetae, but with a very large hood similar to the thoracic paleate chaetae, even if longer. The shape of the chaetae is similar along the abdominal segments even if in the last segments they become longer and with a more geniculate appearance (
<figureCitation box="[414,548,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-212@20.[151,1436,525,1901]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 15. Amphiglena gravinae sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221">Fig. 15G, F</figureCitation>
). Pair of light spermathechae present at the base of dorsal lips.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636176" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4636176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636176/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="221" startId="20.[151,250,1924,1948]" targetBox="[162,1423,539,1894]" targetPageId="20">
